Fuzzy Logic in Classification of Tumor Images¶

This paper will seek to utilize fuzzy logic to classify images of tumors as either benign or malignant using data obtained from the UCI Machine Learning Repository.

We see that there are many potential features here to build our model. For now, we are most focused on the first 10 columns which all describe the mean values for the types of features, (perimeter, area, concavity, etc.) while columns 11-30 are all some form of error measurement from these values. Our final column is our target variable. Let's now perform some exploratory data analysis on the main columns.

EDA¶

In [4]:
def histogram(data,column,bins=50,weights=None,lines=[]):
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    
    axes.set_xlabel(column, fontsize=20)
    axes.set_ylabel("Count", fontsize=20)
    
    chart = axes.hist(data[column], bins=bins, color=mainColor,ec='black',weights=weights)
    
    max_y = max(chart[0])
    axes.vlines(lines,0,max_y+2,color=secondColor,lw=4)
    
    axes.set_title("Histogram of " + column + "; " + str(bins) + " bins", fontsize=25)
    axes.grid(zorder=0)
    
    plt.show()
    plt.close()

def pairwiseEDA(feature):

    fig, (ax1, ax2) = plt.subplots(figsize=(20,6),ncols=2, sharex=True, sharey=True)

    x1=data.groupby('benign')[feature].get_group(0)
    x2=data.groupby('benign')[feature].get_group(1)

    ax1.hist(x1, color=mainColor,ec='black',zorder=2,bins=40)
    ax1.set_xlabel(feature, fontsize=20)
    ax1.set_ylabel("Number", fontsize=20)
    ax1.set_title("Malignant", fontsize=25)
    ax1.grid(zorder=0)

    ax2.hist(x2, color=mainColor,ec='black',zorder=2,bins=40)
    ax2.set_xlabel(feature, fontsize=20)
    ax2.set_title("Benign", fontsize=25)
    ax2.grid(zorder=0)

    plt.show()
    plt.close()

Fuzzification¶

We now begin the process of fuzzifying our features to use in our model. The following fuzzify function takes the column given in the data and creates fuzzy classes with the names provided such as "small", "medium", or "large". We have chosen to create all fuzzy classes with trapezoidal shapes. Our function will take any number of class names (minimum of 2), and create evenly distributed classes across the range of data. We will also create new feature columns in our dataframe, and plot the classes on a chart.

In [37]:
def plotFuzz(divisions, point, point_Y_vals, attribute_name, labels):
    
    figure = plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    axes = figure.add_subplot(1, 1, 1)
    
    first_class_X = [divisions[0],divisions[1],divisions[2]]
    last_class_X = [divisions[-3],divisions[-2],divisions[-1]]
    first_class_Y = [1,1,0]
    last_class_Y = [0,1,1]
    
    position = 1
    middle_classes = []
    for _ in range(int(len(divisions)/2)-2): #for the middle classes
        middle_class_X = [divisions[position],divisions[position+1],divisions[position+2],divisions[position+3]]
        middle_class_Y = [0,1,1,0]
        middle_classes.append([middle_class_X,middle_class_Y])
        position+=2
        
    lw=4
    plt.plot(first_class_X,first_class_Y,lw=lw,label="Class: {}".format(labels[0]))
    for label_index, middle_class in enumerate(middle_classes): #different shape than first and last classes
        plt.plot(middle_class[0],middle_class[1],lw=lw,label="Class: {}".format(labels[label_index+1]))
    plt.plot(last_class_X,last_class_Y,lw=lw,label="Class: {}".format(labels[-1]))
    
    plt.plot(point,point_Y_vals[0],'ko',label="First entry: {}".format(point))
    plt.plot(point,point_Y_vals[1],'ko')
    
    axes.set_xlabel(attribute_name, fontsize=20)
    axes.set_ylabel("Membership Value", fontsize=20)
    axes.set_title("Fuzzy Membership Classes for {}".format(attribute_name), fontsize=25)
    
    plt.legend(bbox_to_anchor=(1.05, 1), loc='upper left', prop={'size': 15})
    plt.show()
    plt.close()
In [38]:
import bisect
import math

def fuzzify(feature_values, class_names): 
    # Here trapezoidal shape is assumed, values in no more than two classes
    classes_length = len(class_names) #can create any fuzzy number of fuzzy classes
    top_trap_length = 1/(classes_length + (classes_length-1)/2) #length of top trapezoidal shape
    side_trap_length = top_trap_length/2 #length of each diagonal
    
    x_axis_divisions = [0] #this will hold a list of all points on x axis where a new class may start to appear
    x_axis_position = 0 #pointer
    
    for i in range(classes_length-1): # "walk" along x axis creating division points from 0 to 1
        x_axis_position += top_trap_length
        x_axis_divisions.append(x_axis_position)
        x_axis_position += side_trap_length
        x_axis_divisions.append(x_axis_position)
    x_axis_divisions.append(1) #to avoid rounding error we explicitly assign this last point
    
    feature_range = max(feature_values) - min(feature_values)
    x_axis_divisions = [x*feature_range+min(feature_values) for x in x_axis_divisions] #scale to feature range
    
    for df_position, value in enumerate(feature_values): #for each value in df, determine membership value in each class

        index_div_position = bisect.bisect_left(x_axis_divisions, value) #find where this value would fall on the fuzzy x axis

        membership_values = {}
        if(index_div_position%2==0):
            low_class_bound = x_axis_divisions[index_div_position-1]
            high_class_bound = x_axis_divisions[index_div_position]
            distance = high_class_bound - low_class_bound

            high_membership = (value-low_class_bound)/distance
            low_membership = 1 - high_membership

            lower_class = class_names[math.floor(index_div_position/2)-1]
            membership_values[lower_class] = low_membership
            
            upper_class = class_names[math.floor(index_div_position/2)]
            membership_values[upper_class] = high_membership
            
            if value==min(feature_values): #for plotting, special case of bisect
                low_membership = 1 
           
        else:
            low_membership = 1
            high_membership = 1

            upper_class = class_names[math.floor(index_div_position/2)]
            membership_values[upper_class] = high_membership
        
        for class_name in class_names:
            if membership_values.get(class_name) is not None:
                data.at[df_position, "Fuzzy {} class: {}".format(feature_values.name,class_name)] = membership_values.get(class_name)
            else:
                data.at[df_position, "Fuzzy {} class: {}".format(feature_values.name,class_name)] = 0

        if(df_position==0): #plot first point
            plotFuzz(x_axis_divisions, value, [low_membership, high_membership], feature_values.name, class_names)
    
    return x_axis_divisions

Evaluation & Results¶

Let's try to build some rules now utilizing radius and concavity:

IF (radius is X-large) THEN tumor is malignant
IF (radius is small) THEN tumor is benign
IF (radius is large OR medium) AND (concavity is low) THEN tumor is benign
IF (radius is large OR medium) AND (smoothness is moderate or severe) THEN tumor is malignant

In [42]:
def defuzzifyTest():
    
    #sum membership values and weight each component of rule evenly
    rule1 = data["Fuzzy mean radius class: X-Large"]
    rule2 = data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Small"]
    rule3 = (data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Large"] + data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Medium"]
            + data["Fuzzy mean concavity class: Low"]) / 3
    rule4 = (data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Large"] + data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Medium"]
            + data["Fuzzy mean concavity class: Moderate"] + data["Fuzzy mean concavity class: Severe"]) / 4

    #weight "benign" and "malignant" rules evenly
    data["fuzzy_output_malignant"] = (rule1 + rule4 )/2
    data["fuzzy_output_benign"] = (rule2 + rule3 )/2

    #majority will be winner
    data['crisp_output_test'] = data.apply(lambda x : 1 if x['fuzzy_output_malignant'] > x['fuzzy_output_benign'] else 0, axis=1)

def evaluateMetrics(predictions,actuals):
    
    #Find true/false positives/negatives

    true_positives = 0
    true_negatives = 0
    false_positives = 0
    false_negatives = 0

    for index,prediction in enumerate(predictions):
        if(actuals[index] == prediction):
            if(prediction == 1):
                true_positives += 1
            else:
                true_negatives +=1
        elif(prediction == 1):
            false_positives += 1
        else:
            false_negatives += 1
            
    return true_positives, true_negatives, false_positives, false_negatives

Rules:¶

IF (radius is X-large) THEN tumor is malignant
IF (radius is small) THEN tumor is benign
IF (radius is large OR medium) AND (smoothness is smooth) THEN tumor is benign
IF (radius is large OR medium) AND (smoothness is medium or rough) THEN tumor is malignant

def defuzzify():
    
    #sum membership values and weight each component of rule evenly
    rule1 = data["Fuzzy mean radius class: X-Large"]
    rule2 = data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Small"]
    rule3 = (data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Large"] + data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Medium"]
            + data["Fuzzy mean smoothness class: Smooth"]) / 3
    rule4 = (data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Large"] + data["Fuzzy mean radius class: Medium"]

We see our preliminary results above, and as we can see we have greatly increased our sensitivity, albeit at the cost of precision. We now want to accomplish two things: compare these results to a more standard baseline model and validate these results as more robust by simulating the experiments many times using the bootstrap method.

Comparison to Logistic Regression Model¶

We choose to utilize the logistic regression model from sklearn. Though not shown here, many sets of features were tried and the same features used in our fuzzy model "mean radius" and "mean smoothness" were shown to provide either the best result within a range of 0.1 or came at the cost of worsening another metric. For convenience and ease of comparison, we therefore ultimately chose these features to train our regression model. We also evaluate our fuzzy bootstrap metrics on the same test set for each iteration of our simulation to ensure comparable results.

In [60]:
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression
In [61]:
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
num_bootstrap_samples = 100

features = ['mean radius', 'mean smoothness'] #logistic regression featues
feature_x_vals = [np.array(data[feature]).reshape(-1,1) for feature in features]

X = np.concatenate(feature_x_vals,axis=1)
y = data['malignant'].values

#fuzzy bootstrap metrics, will have 100 values by end
fuzzy_bs_precisions = []
fuzzy_bs_sensitivities = []
fuzzy_bs_specificities = []

#fuzzy log regression metrics, will have 100 values by end
log_precisions = []
log_sensitivities = []
log_specificities = []

reg = LogisticRegression() #create logistic regressor

for boostrap_sample in range(num_bootstrap_samples):
    fuzzy_predictions_boostrap = []
    
    x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.4, random_state=boostrap_sample) #create train and test data
    
    for x in range(len(x_test)): 
        row = data[(data[features[0]]==x_test[x][0]) & (data[features[1]]==x_test[x][1])] #find the row being tested in log regressor
        crisp = row['crisp_output'].values[0] #find the crisp output determined from the fuzzy rules here
        fuzzy_predictions_boostrap.append(crisp) #append to fuzzy results
    
    fuzzy_bs_tp, fuzzy_bs_tn, fuzzy_bs_fp, fuzzy_bs_fn = evaluateMetrics(fuzzy_predictions_boostrap,y_test)
    
    fuzzy_bs_precision = get_precision(fuzzy_bs_tp, fuzzy_bs_tn, fuzzy_bs_fp, fuzzy_bs_fn)
    fuzzy_bs_sensitivity = get_sensitivity(fuzzy_bs_tp, fuzzy_bs_tn, fuzzy_bs_fp, fuzzy_bs_fn)
    fuzzy_bs_specificity = get_specificity(fuzzy_bs_tp, fuzzy_bs_tn, fuzzy_bs_fp, fuzzy_bs_fn)
    
    #create fuzzy bootstrap results
    fuzzy_bs_precisions.append(fuzzy_bs_precision)
    fuzzy_bs_sensitivities.append(fuzzy_bs_sensitivity)
    fuzzy_bs_specificities.append(fuzzy_bs_specificity)

    reg.fit(x_train, y_train) #fit standard model
    
    log_predictions = reg.predict(x_test)
    log_tp, log_tn, log_fp, log_fn = evaluateMetrics(log_predictions,y_test)
    
    log_precision = get_precision(log_tp, log_tn, log_fp, log_fn)
    log_sensitivity = get_sensitivity(log_tp, log_tn, log_fp, log_fn)
    log_specificity = get_specificity(log_tp, log_tn, log_fp, log_fn)
     
    #create standard log bootstrap results
    log_precisions.append(log_precision)
    log_sensitivities.append(log_sensitivity)
    log_specificities.append(log_specificity)
